{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564597"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:16:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:16:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16993"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16993","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16993"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.16,0.59,0.04,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9683"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68165"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9683"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16993"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53622"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2118"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4128"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"12245"},{"type":"tags","id":"12250"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"},{"type":"tags","id":"12807"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22814"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45155"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68165"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with worsening right-sided abdominal and flank pain for two days. She underwent a total laparoscopic hysterectomy five days ago for heavy menstrual bleeding. The operation was noted to be difficult due to extensive pelvic adhesions and bleeding from the right uterine artery requiring additional haemostatic measures. Her initial post-operative course was uncomplicated and she was discharged home on day one.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft with right-sided tenderness and mild costovertebral angle tenderness. Her laparoscopic port sites are clean and healing well.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum creatinine: 145 \u03bcmol/L (45-90)\u003Cbr /\u003EWhite cell count: 12.5 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0)\u003Cbr /\u003EC-reactive protein: 85 mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cystoscopy","Transvaginal ultrasound","CT urogram","Nuclear medicine renal scan","Magnetic resonance imaging pelvis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with concerning features of a ureteric injury following total laparoscopic hysterectomy. The combination of new onset flank pain, rising creatinine, and the history of a difficult surgical dissection near the right uterine artery (which runs in close proximity to the ureter) should raise suspicion for this complication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT urogram\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard investigation for suspected ureteric injury. It can demonstrate the location and extent of injury, identify urine extravasation, and assess for hydronephrosis or urinoma formation. It also provides information about other potential post-operative complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransvaginal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful for identifying pelvic collections but has limited utility in diagnosing ureteric injuries. It cannot reliably visualise the entire course of the ureter or identify the site of injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging\u003C/strong\u003E of the pelvis can provide detailed anatomical information but is not the first-line investigation for suspected ureteric injury. It is more time-consuming and less readily available than CT urogram.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECystoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful to identify lower urinary tract injuries and to assist with ureteric stent placement, but it is not the initial investigation of choice for suspected ureteric injury. It may be required as part of the treatment plan once the diagnosis is confirmed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENuclear medicine renal scan\u003C/strong\u003E can demonstrate differential renal function but lacks the anatomical detail needed to plan surgical intervention. It is more commonly used for chronic conditions affecting renal function rather than acute ureteric injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUreteric injury is reported to occur in 0.5-2.5% of total laparoscopic hysterectomies, with higher rates in complex cases involving adhesions or difficult dissection. Early recognition is crucial as delayed diagnosis can lead to significant morbidity including urinoma formation, sepsis, and potential loss of renal function.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ureteric injury is a recognised complication of total laparoscopic hysterectomy, particularly in cases with adhesions or difficult dissection.","Post-operative flank pain with rising creatinine should raise suspicion for ureteric injury.","CT urogram is the gold standard investigation for suspected ureteric injury."],"references":["Manoucheri E, Cohen SL, Sandberg EM, Kibel AS, Einarsson J. Ureteral injury in laparoscopic gynecologic surgery. Rev Obstet Gynecol. 2012;5(2):106-11. PMID: 22866190; PMCID: PMC3410510."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53622"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16993"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53622","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53622"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T14:10:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T14:11:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9683"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68165"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships"